It is known that the following proposition holds by defining the inner product as in (\ref{eq:inner_product}).

\begin{proposition}[Properties of the copositive cone]
\label{prop:conic_duality}
\begin{description}
\item[(i)] The dual cone of the copositive cone ${\cal COP}_n$ with respect to the inner product (\ref{eq:inner_product}) is the completely positive cone ${\cal CP}_n$ and vice versa (see p.57 of \cite{bBERMAN73} and Theorem 2.3 of \cite{bBERMAN03}).
\item[(ii)] If $n \leq 4$, then ${\cal COP}_n = {\cal S}_n^+ + {\cal N}_n$ (see \cite{aDIANANDA62} and Proposition 1.23 of \cite{bBERMAN03}). 
\item[(iii)] The dual cone of the doubly nonnegative cone ${\cal S}_n^+ \cap {\cal N}_n$ with respect to the inner product (\ref{eq:inner_product}) is the Minkowski sum ${\cal S}_n^+ + {\cal N}_n$ of the positive semidefinite cone ${\cal S}_n^+$ and the nonnegative cone ${\cal N}_n$, and vice versa (see Remark \ref{rem:Fenchel}).
\end{description}
\end{proposition}

\begin{remark}
\label{rem:Fenchel}
Proposition \ref{prop:conic_duality} (iii): The equality $({\cal S}_n^+ \cap {\cal N}_n )^* = {{\rm cl}\,} ({\cal S}_n^+ + {\cal N}_n )$ follows from a well-known result that $({\cal K}_1 \cap {\cal K}_2 )^* = {{\rm cl}\,} ({\cal K}_1 + {\cal K}_2)$ holds for any closed convex cones ${\cal K}_1$ and ${\cal K}_2$ (see, e.g., p. 11 of \cite{bFENCHEL53} or Corollary 2.2 of \cite{bBERMAN73}). The closedness of the set ${\cal S}_n^+ + {\cal N}_n$ follows from a result presented in \cite{bROCKAFELLAR98}. See also Proposition 4.1 of \cite{aYOSHISE10}, where the authors showed this property within a more general framework. 
\end{remark}

